== Description ==
The '''Juju Man''', also alluded to as '''Epiales''', the '''Lord of Nightmares''', is an anomalous humanoid [[Entity List|entity]] who has been witnessed wandering the halls of [[the Backrooms]]. Although defined by himself as an eldritch immortal who is able to take on many different forms, he has only ever been definitively documented assuming the shape of a tall, middle-aged anthropoid figure garbed in a monochromatic outfit.<ref>Even while stalking the subconscious of wanderers, the Juju Man maintains this singular shape, strangely rigid compared to the shifting forms of dreams and nightmares.</ref> His garments include a large grey fedora which obscures his face at all times, a dusty black overcoat worn over a formal shirt and trousers, a belt to which a large metal ring of keys is constantly attached, and occasionally a silver-topped walking cane. 

The keys belonging to the '''Juju Man''' largely act as charms and talismans enabling him to work his anomalous powers. Some of these are simply [[Object 2|level keys]], but many are rumoured to be possessed of far stranger and more wondrous mysticism. The most arcane of these keys are, according to the Juju Man, able to unlock and penetrate deep into a wanderer's soul; to read their most primal loves, hatreds and fears; to warp them to his own will. All the talismanic keys of the Juju Man are impalpable to mortals, and those unfortunate souls who have come into contact with them have been known to <s>dissolve into nothingness</s> ''be [[Leftovers|erased from genuine existence]]''. 

The '''Juju Man''' is the self-proclaimed Lord of Nightmares. In the entity's own words, <div class="juju-text">
:Do you know what a nightmare is? It is very different from a dream. Most of the experiences you mortals would call nightmares are, in fact, just dreams of a more morbid nature. But perhaps I am talking myself in circles trying to explain all of this to you in your own language, which bears not terms enough to describe the workings of the wider cosmos. 

:The mortal mind can be fragmented into three basic aspects. There is ''thought'', which is composed of ideas, opinions, solutions, judgements. ''Thought'' comprises the main body of [[the Void]]'s kaleidoscopic ocean which you term the Akashic Field. There is ''emotion'', which comprises subtler, more instinctive feelings that permeate the mind and influence ''thought''. ''Emotion'' lurks in the depths of the Akashic, in an underlying area you term the Empathic Subfield. And there is the ''essence'', the ''soul'', which predates the Akashic and has existed since the very beginning. The ''essence'' knows only three core feelings to which all the mind is a slave: Love, Hatred, and their child, Fear. 

:A true nightmare is one that harnesses the potential of the ''soul''. Not one formed of ''thought'' and ''emotion'', as most dreams are, but of raw ''essence''. One so bizarre and so delirious that ''thought'' cannot comprehend it and ''emotion'' cannot grasp it. I am the Lord of Nightmares, the sole facilitator of the cosmic, incomprehensible terrors that haunt the minds of the slumbering. For I am the only one who holds the keys unto the soul. </div>

The full extent of the '''Juju Man'''<nowiki />'s abilities is unknown, but rumours often allege that the keys in which his power is apparently contained possess higher-order capabilities such as recalling the dead, warping the fabrics of space and time, and restringing the metaphysical to his will. The entity is also often causes lights and screens around him to flicker, and his presence is most distinctly recognised by the distortion of sounds and other sensations. Many reports describe his appearance quivering in and out of existence, as if he were not truly present. Whether these supposed abilities hail from the Juju Man's talismans, or are innate powers which he himself possesses, is difficult to ascertain. 

== Behaviour ==
The existence of the '''Juju Man''' has never been formally declared. Based on eyewitness recounts, the entity typically appears to a wanderer as a sort of shadow in their peripheral vision, standing silent and motionless, simply staring: staring "into their soul", as many witnesses word it. Usually, he only manifests perceivably to one mind at a time,<ref>Some small groups have reported all encountering the Juju Man simultaneously.</ref> and is seemingly unaffected by anything actually occurring in his surrounding area; in this way, his definition is closer to that of a hallucination than a genuine entity. He does not even need to be seen; even the blind can sense his presence as a subtle, incessant feeling of unease. In almost every case, wanderers have reported that the Juju Man stays in this state of soundless observation, before vanishing completely in the blink of an eye. 

On occasion, wanderers have described that, upon the '''Juju Man'''<nowiki />'s sudden disappearance, a single one of his key-shaped charms would be left behind to perform a feat of reality warping power.<ref>A select few cases describe the Juju Man leaving a [[Object 2|level key]] behind. These do not warp reality and can be retrieved by the wanderer for their own use, and do not disappear of their own accord.</ref> Such a key could cause any number of the miraculous occurrences listed above under the entity's talismanic powers (most notably, severe spatial distortion, temporary recollection of the deceased, and random, bizarre visions), before imploding upon itself and returning everything to "normal". Witnesses have described a nagging feeling of incomprehensible emotion departing as soon as the Juju Man's key vanished, as if their heart and their surroundings had exhaled a long-held breath. 

The '''Juju Man''' sometimes stalks the dreams and nightmares of wanderers. Unlike other oneirological phenomena, those who dream of him maintain an unnaturally distinct memory of his appearance and demeanour even after waking; and he almost never presents as a recurring element, only ever visiting the dreams of his chosen minds once in their lifetimes. It is only in these subconscious moments that he actually converses with wanderers, and much of what is supposedly known of his nature has been revealed from his own mouth in this fashion. 

== Origins ==
Documentations and depictions of the '''Juju Man''' have existed for an extremely long period of time, making it difficult to discern when exactly he emerged into the Backrooms. Cave art in an unidentified sub-level of [[Level 8]], which has been xenon-dated to 400,000 years ago and was presumably composed by [[Entity 70|''Homo callidus'']], portray a grey figure clothed in garments reminiscent of the Juju Man's attire, including his signature fedora and keyring. These artworks include strange, multicoloured lines and patterns surrounding their central figure, perhaps alluding to the entity's supposed control over nightmares. The ancient Greek epic known as the [[Entity 18|''Phrikeid'']] included a fleeting appearance of what is presumably the Juju Man, who leaves a [[Object 2|level key]] for the [[Entity 18|Beast of Level 5]] upon encountering him in [[Level 3]]. 

Expert parascientists who have personally encountered the '''Juju Man''' state that he is not a [[Phenomenon 9|tulpa]]. In the words of acclaimed tulpologist Dr Alicia Bond, ''"a tulpa is an anomalous formation caused by collective thought or belief resulting in the creation of a physical construct, often abnormal in nature. Our dear friend Epiales is not a physical construct, nor is he caused by a collective mental state or a potent personal desire (this latter option refers to the process of [[Phenomenon 9-A|thoughtformation]]); he is more akin to a hallucination or an illusion, in this respect... However, as someone who has met him once in waking life and once in my sleep, and has spoken to many others who have encountered him, I cannot say that he is influenced by the witness's personal experience, history or emotional state either... It is hard to understand what I mean unless you have also met him. But in this way, he cannot be a hallucination... Neither can he be an illusion, on the account of the [[Object 2|level keys]] he leaves behind... The Juju Man is an anomaly in the [[The Kauer Thesis|Kauer Thesis]]."''

Perhaps the answer lies in [[brokenology]]. If the '''Juju Man''' scientifically resembles nothing ever conventionally encountered in the Backrooms before, perhaps he does not originate from the Backrooms at all. The Broken Theorem names a force known as the "broken tendency", defined as the tendency of B-materials to fall into [[the Broken]] if no normal force is applied — yet what if there was an equal and opposite force to this, a "wake tendency"? Brokenologists have theorised that the Juju Man is [[Leftovers|not a real, genuinely existent being]], and is simply the result of the Broken transferring non-matter into the Backrooms as an antithetical reaction to hypernoclippage. 

A recurring theme in conversations the '''Juju Man''' holds with those wanderers whose dreams he infiltrates is the fact that he is incarcerated and deprived of his true form and power. In accordance with this, his keys could be variously interpreted as fragments of his scattered power which he has found, as external sources of an anomalous nature which he harnesses as a supplement, or perhaps as literal keys to a "prison", discarded attempts at liberating himself from his imprisonment. Other than this detail, however, theorists have found no other conclusive particulars to which to link this notion of the Juju Man as a mere avatar of an incarcerated higher being. 

